docs.lead_paragraph: The United States mail Steamship ?? Capt. WOTTON, arrived at this port last evening, from Havre and Southampton, bringing London dates to Nov. 18. The leading features of the news she brings were given on Monday, in our telegraphic dispatches from St. Johns--the steamer having been intercepted off Cape Race by the news yacht of the associated Press.

docs.lead_paragraph: MORTALITY IN BROOKLYN.--During the week ending Saturday last, the Health Officer, Dr. CLEVELAND, reports 95 deaths: Males, 51: Females. 44; Men, 21; Boys, 30; Women 19; Girls, 25. DISEASES.--Consumption, 14; stillborn, 9; disease of the brain, 7; inflammation of the lungs, 6; convulsions and scarlet fever, 5 each; premature birth, inflammation of bowels, 4 each; congestion of lungs, chronic diarrhoea, marasmus, small pox, trismus, old age, apoplexy, typhoid fever, sprue, 2 each; ; bron.

docs.lead_paragraph: ARRIVAL OF THE QUAKER CITY -- DECLINE IN SEGAR --FREIGHTS DULL. The steamship Quaker City, Capt. SHUFELDT, from Mobile on the night of the 22nd, and Havana at 5 P.M. on the 25th, arrived hore last evening. she experienced very heavy weather nearly the whole passage. There is nothing new from Havana. The health of the City is prefect.

docs.lead_paragraph: The friends of Mayor WOOD, driven to desporation by the dangerous condition of their patient's health, are putting up their prayers to ESCULAPIUS. "Minions of tile moon," as they are, and votaries of Mercury, they have discovered or fancy that they have discovered a notable well on the character of Mr. TIEMANN, by virtue of which they expect to recombine the dissolute energies of their fainting FBRNANDO.

docs.lead_paragraph: The War Between Casta Rien and Niearngun. We gave yesterday, in our Central American Correspondence, particulars of the outbreak that has recently occurred between Nicaragua and Costs Rical. Among the official documents sent us by our correspondent were letters from Col. CAUTY, commander of the River San Juan, demanding, on the part of Costs Riea, the surrender of that river and its forts from the Nienraguan authorities.
